# Line endings for the files whose exact bytes are load-bearing.
#
# Two things break if these are ever checked out with CRLF:
#
#   1. A shell script with CRLF line endings fails on Linux with a
#      "bad interpreter: /bin/sh^M" that nobody can read.
#   2. site/*.sha256 pins the digest of the file a user downloads and is told
#      to verify before piping into a shell. If a contributor on Windows
#      checks the script out as CRLF, re-uploads it, and the download page
#      still quotes the LF digest, the one user who bothered to check gets a
#      mismatch -- and learns that checking is not worth doing.
#
# Git on Windows defaults to core.autocrlf=true, so without this file the
# second case is not hypothetical.

*.sh        text eol=lf
*.ps1       text eol=lf
*.sha256    text eol=lf

# The installer payloads again, by name, so that renaming the pattern above
# can never quietly stop covering the files the digests are computed over.
site/install.sh     text eol=lf
site/install.ps1    text eol=lf
site/uninstall.sh   text eol=lf
site/uninstall.ps1  text eol=lf

# THE PAGES ARE HASHED TOO, and this was missed until CI said so.
#
# The CSP pins each page's inline <script> by sha256 (deploy/Caddyfile,
# deploy/nginx/security-headers.conf, deploy/nginx/yangble5.com.conf.example
# and site/README.md all carry the value). The hash is taken over the script
# body as it appears in the file, so a CRLF checkout produces a different
# digest for the same source. On a GitHub windows-latest runner, where
# core.autocrlf defaults to true, that failed every Windows job on all five
# Python versions while every Linux job passed -- the signature of a checkout
# problem rather than a code one.
#
# tools/drift_check.py compares these bytes against what the live site serves,
# which is a second reason they cannot be allowed to vary by platform.
site/*.html         text eol=lf

# The agent-facing surface, added when tools/drift_check.py started comparing it
# against the live site byte for byte. Same reasoning as the pages above: a CRLF
# checkout changes bytes nobody edited, and the failure surfaces on Windows only.
site/AGENTS.md                  text eol=lf
site/llms.txt                   text eol=lf
site/sitemap.xml                text eol=lf
site/.well-known/*              text eol=lf

# The configs that CARRY those pins. Their bytes are not hashed, but a file
# that must be diffed against a deployed copy should not change shape by
# checkout either.
deploy/Caddyfile                            text eol=lf
deploy/nginx/*.conf                         text eol=lf
deploy/nginx/*.conf.example                 text eol=lf
